    <section class="design-system-section panel-beta panel--wide">
        <div class="grid-width">
            <h3 class="design-system-headline" id="form-fragments">Form Fragments (question groups)</h3>
            <p>Form fragments are the highest grouping level in our forms. They split the form into chunks each of which contains one to many questions that are related to one-another by some kind of theme.</p>

            <strong class="design-system-example">Example:</strong>
            <form action="/without-js-it-submits-to-this-url" method="post">
                <div class="question-group">
                    <div class="form-fragment">
                        <h2 class="form-fragment-title">Form fragment title</h2>
                        <div class="form-fragment-content">
                            One to many questions are put here inside the form fragment content. Note: the first form fragment doesn't get a divider keyline.
                        </div>
                    </div>
                </div>
                <div class="question-group">
                    <div class="form-fragment">
                        <h2 class="form-fragment-title">Form fragment title</h2>
                        <div class="form-fragment-content">
                            Note: this form fragment gets a keyline above it to separate it from the previous form fragment.
                        </div>
                    </div>
                </div>
            </form>
        </div>
    </section>

    <section class="design-system-section panel-inverse panel--wide">
        <div class="grid-width">
            <h3 class="design-system-headline" id="questions-and-options">Questions, and question options</h3>
            <p>A form question has a type eg. text, number, radio, checkbox, date, percentage breakdown, etc. Questions may have one or many question options. A multi-option question may have multiple text fields to fill in, or multiple radio buttons or checkboxes to choose from. When a question has multiple options it should always have a 'legend' which introduces the question. Each question option has a label which is attached to the choice or text input field that the user chooses. Clicking on this label should always activate the question.</p>
            <p>A question can have one of a few states:</p>
            <ul>
                <li>An inactive state</li>
                <li>An active state</li>
                <li>A success state</li>
                <li>An error state</li>
            </ul>

            <p><strong class="design-system-example">Text question example (showing error state):</strong></p>
            <form action="/without-js-it-submits-to-this-url" method="post">
                <fieldset>
                    <div class="text question question-error">
                        <div class="question-main">
                            <legend>Name of Applicant
                                <a class="help-message-trigger"><i class="icon-info"></i></a>
                                <span class="help-message-text">Mobile help text for this question, eg. this input text will be used to get you a quote&hellip;</span>
                            </legend>
                            <div class="option error">
                                <div class="row">
                                    <div class="label-selector"></div>
                                    <div class="input-and-unit">
                                        <input type="text" placeholder="e.g. J. Smith t/as J.S. Associates" maxlength="100">
                                    </div>
                                </div>
                                <p class="error-message"><i class="icon-error"></i>Please enter the name of applicant</p>
                            </div>
                        </div>
                    </div>
                    <div class="question-aside"><div class="help-message-text">Desktop help text. eg. this input text will be used to get you a quote&hellip;</div>
                    </div>
                </fieldset>
            </form>
        </div>
    </section>

